<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter xml:id="ch-poissonreg" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Poisson Regression</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>Chapter goals:</p>
    <objectives>
      <ul>
        <li><p>Explain situations in which Poisson regression is preferred to ordinary least squares regression.</p></li>
        <li><p>Describe key assumptions of Poisson regression models.</p></li>
        <li><p>Interpret coefficients from Poisson regression models, including rate ratios.</p></li>
        <li><p>Use deviance and likelihood-based tests for model comparison and goodness-of-fit.</p></li>
        <li><p>Address overdispersion using quasi-Poisson or negative binomial regression.</p></li>
        <li><p>Use offsets to model rates and account for differences in exposure.</p></li>
        <li><p>Describe and fit zero-inflated Poisson (ZIP) models for data with excess zeros.</p></li>
      </ul>
    </objectives>

    <p>In this chapter, we consider data sets in which the responses are <term>counts</term>: non-negative integers that represent the number of occurrences of some event.  Examples include the number of calls received by a call center per hour, the number of flaws found in a roll of fabric, or the number of children in a household. Rather than using ordinary least squares regression for counts, we turn to <term>Poisson regression</term>, which respects the discrete, non-negative nature of the response and links the mean count to predictor variables through a log link function.</p>

    <p>R packages needed for this chapter:</p>
    <program language="r" xml:id="code-ch4-packages">
      <input>
library(tidyverse)
library(knitr)
library(gridExtra)
library(kableExtra)
library(multcomp)
library(MASS)
library(pscl)
      </input>
    </program>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-intro-poisson">
    <title>Introduction to Poisson Regression</title>

    <p>Recall from <xref ref="ch-distthry"/> that if <m>Y \sim \textrm{Poisson}(\lambda)</m>, then both the mean and variance of <m>Y</m> equal <m>\lambda</m>. The <term>Poisson regression</term> <idx>Poisson regression</idx> model links one or more explanatory variables to a Poisson response variable.  Given explanatory variables <m>X_1, X_2, \ldots, X_p</m>, we model the mean count <m>\lambda</m> via
    <me>
      \log(\lambda) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 + \cdots + \beta_p X_p,
    </me>
    or equivalently,
    <me>
      \lambda = e^{\beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 + \cdots + \beta_p X_p}.
    </me>
    </p>

    <p>Because counts are necessarily non-negative and the exponential function always produces positive values, the Poisson regression model respects this constraint automatically. Compare this to ordinary least squares (OLS) regression, where a fitted linear model could produce negative predicted values when the response can only be zero or positive.</p>

    <subsection xml:id="sec-pois-assumptions">
      <title>Poisson Regression Assumptions</title>
      <p>The key assumptions of Poisson regression are:</p>
      <p><ol>
        <li><p><term>Poisson response</term>: the response variable is a count that follows a Poisson distribution.</p></li>
        <li><p><term>Independence</term>: the observations are independent of one another.</p></li>
        <li><p><term>Mean equals variance</term>: as implied by the Poisson distribution, the mean and variance of the count response are equal.</p></li>
        <li><p><term>Linearity</term>: the log of the mean count, <m>\log(\lambda)</m>, is a linear function of the predictors.</p></li>
      </ol></p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="sec-pois-graphical">
      <title>A Graphical Look at Poisson Regression</title>
      <p>Figure <xref ref="fig-OLSpois"/> compares OLS and Poisson regression. In OLS, the conditional distribution of <m>Y</m> given <m>X</m> is assumed to be normal with constant variance. In contrast, Poisson regression assumes the conditional distribution is Poisson, with mean (and variance) that changes as a function of <m>X</m>. Note that we plot <m>\log(\bar{Y})</m> against <m>X</m> (rather than <m>\bar{Y}</m> against <m>X</m>) when assessing the linearity assumption, since the model is linear in <m>\log(\lambda)</m>.</p>

      <figure xml:id="fig-OLSpois">
        <caption>Comparing OLS regression (left) and Poisson regression (right). In OLS, the conditional distributions are normal with constant variance. In Poisson regression, the conditional distributions are Poisson with mean equal to variance, both of which change with <m>X</m>.</caption>
        <image source="generated-assets/fig-OLSpois.png" width="80%">
          <description>Two panels comparing OLS and Poisson regression. The left panel shows bell curves of equal height at each X value. The right panel shows Poisson distributions that grow and spread as X increases.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </subsection>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-cs-philippines">
    <title>Case Study: Household Size in the Philippines</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>Our first case study uses data from the 2015 Philippine Statistics Authority Family Income and Expenditure Survey (FIES). We will use Poisson regression to model the number of people living in a household using age of the household head and region as predictors. </p>
    </introduction>

    <subsection xml:id="organizedata4">
      <title>Data Organization</title>

      <p>The data set <c>Philippines.csv</c> contains variables from 1,500 households sampled from the 2015 FIES. The response variable is <c>total</c>, the total number of people in the household, which is a count. Potential explanatory variables include <c>age</c> (age of the household head in years), <c>location</c> (Urban or Rural), <c>numLT5</c> (number of household members under age 5), and <c>region</c> (geographic region of the Philippines).  Figure <xref ref="fig-philippinesmap"/> shows the regions of the Philippines.</p>

      <figure xml:id="fig-philippinesmap">
        <caption>Map of the Philippines showing its three main island groups (Luzon, Visayas, and Mindanao) and major regions.</caption>
        <image source="data/map_of_philippines.jpg" width="50%">
          <description>A map of the Philippines showing its archipelago and labeled regions used in the case study.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <program language="r" xml:id="code-ch4-philippines-load">
        <input>
phil &lt;- read.csv("data/Philippines.csv")
        </input>
      </program>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="exploreHH">
      <title>Exploratory Data Analyses</title>

      <p>We begin with a histogram of <c>total</c>, the number of people in the household. Figure <xref ref="fig-nhouse"/> shows the distribution of household sizes. The majority of households have between 2 and 6 people, and the distribution is right-skewed. The sample mean is about 4.7 people per household and the variance is close to the mean, providing initial evidence that a Poisson model may be appropriate.</p>

      <figure xml:id="fig-nhouse">
        <caption>Histogram of the number of people in a household (Philippines data).</caption>
        <image source="generated-assets/fig-nhouse.png" width="60%">
          <description>A histogram of household size showing right-skewed distribution with most households having 2 to 6 members.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <p>To assess the linearity assumption, we compute the mean household size for each age group and plot the log of the mean against age (Figure <xref ref="fig-totalPoisByAge"/>). The relationship between log mean household size and age appears reasonably linear, supporting the linearity assumption.</p>

      <figure xml:id="fig-totalPoisByAge">
        <caption>Log of mean household size by age group of household head (Philippines data). The roughly linear trend supports the Poisson regression linearity assumption.</caption>
        <image source="generated-assets/fig-totalPoisByAge.png" width="60%">
          <description>Scatterplot of log mean household size vs. age group of household head with a roughly linear trend.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <p>Figure <xref ref="fig-ageXnhouse"/> shows a scatterplot of household size against age of the household head. The mean count (blue line) shows an inverted-U shape: household size tends to increase in early adulthood, peak, and then decrease as children grow up and leave home. This suggests that a quadratic term in age might improve the model.</p>

      <figure xml:id="fig-ageXnhouse">
        <caption>Household size versus age of the household head (Philippines data). The smoothed mean (blue curve) suggests a quadratic relationship.</caption>
        <image source="generated-assets/fig-ageXnhouse.png" width="60%">
          <description>Scatterplot of household size vs. age of household head with a smoothed line showing an inverted-U shape.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <p>Figure <xref ref="fig-byregion"/> displays mean household size by region. The Central Visayas and ARMM (Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao) regions tend to have the largest households, while the National Capital Region tends to have the smallest. Regional variation motivates including region as a covariate.</p>

      <figure xml:id="fig-byregion">
        <caption>Mean household size by region of the Philippines. Regions are ordered from smallest to largest mean.</caption>
        <image source="generated-assets/fig-byregion.png" width="70%">
          <description>Bar chart of mean household size by Philippines region, showing notable variation across regions.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="sec-PoisInference">
      <title>Estimation and Inference</title>

      <p>We first fit a simple Poisson regression model using only age of the household head as a predictor:</p>

      <program language="r" xml:id="code-ch4-pois-fit1">
        <input>
pois.fit1 &lt;- glm(total ~ age, 
                  family = poisson, data = phil)
summary(pois.fit1)
        </input>
      </program>

      <p>With only age as a predictor, the fitted model is:
      <me>
        \log(\hat{\lambda}) = 1.5789 - 0.00655 \cdot \textrm{age},
      </me>
      or equivalently, <m>\hat{\lambda} = e^{1.5789 - 0.00655 \cdot \textrm{age}}</m>.</p>

      <p>The coefficient for age (<m>\hat{\beta}_1 = -0.00655</m>) is negative, suggesting that mean household size decreases as the age of the household head increases, after accounting for the inverted-U pattern visible in the EDA. The corresponding rate ratio is obtained by exponentiating the coefficient:
      <men xml:id="eq-rateRatio">
        e^{\hat{\beta}_1} = e^{-0.00655} \approx 0.9935.
      </men>
      </p>

      <p>We interpret the rate ratio as follows: for each one-year increase in the age of the household head, the mean number of household members is multiplied by 0.9935 (a decrease of about 0.65%), holding all other predictors constant. We call <m>e^{\hat{\beta}_j}</m> the <term>rate ratio</term> <idx>rate ratio</idx> for predictor <m>X_j</m>.</p>

      <p>Wald-type inference for a Poisson regression coefficient <m>\beta_j</m> uses the test statistic
      <me>
        Z = \frac{\hat{\beta}_j}{SE(\hat{\beta}_j)},
      </me>
      which follows an approximate standard Normal distribution under <m>H_0: \beta_j = 0</m>. The p-value of the age predictor is very small (p &lt; 0.001), providing strong evidence that age is related to household size.</p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="sec-Devtocompare">
      <title>Using Deviances to Compare Models</title>

      <p>The <term>deviance</term> <idx>deviance</idx> of a Poisson regression model measures how well the model fits the data, analogous to the residual sum of squares in OLS regression. The <term>residual deviance</term> is twice the log-likelihood difference between a saturated model (one parameter per observation) and the fitted model. A large residual deviance relative to its degrees of freedom (residual deviance / df <m>\gg</m> 1) suggests lack of fit.</p>

      <p>We can compare two nested Poisson models using a <term>drop-in-deviance test</term> <idx>drop-in-deviance test</idx>. The test statistic is
      <me>
        G^2 = D(\textrm{reduced}) - D(\textrm{full}),
      </me>
      where <m>D</m> denotes residual deviance. Under the null hypothesis that the reduced model is adequate, <m>G^2</m> follows an approximate chi-squared distribution with degrees of freedom equal to the difference in the number of parameters between the two models.</p>

      <program language="r" xml:id="code-ch4-deviance-test">
        <input>
pois.fit2 &lt;- glm(total ~ age + I(age^2), 
                  family = poisson, data = phil)
anova(pois.fit1, pois.fit2, test = "Chisq")
        </input>
      </program>

      <p>The drop-in-deviance test strongly favors the model with the quadratic term (<m>G^2 = 120.6</m>, df = 1, p &lt; .001), consistent with the inverted-U pattern observed in the EDA.</p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="likelihood-sec">
      <title>Using Likelihoods to Fit Models</title>

      <p>Poisson regression coefficients are estimated by <term>maximum likelihood</term> <idx>maximum likelihood</idx>. Assuming observations are independent, each with a Poisson distribution, the likelihood for all <m>n</m> observations is
      <men xml:id="eq-poisLoglik">
        L(\boldsymbol{\beta}) = \prod_{i=1}^{n} \frac{e^{-\lambda_i} \lambda_i^{y_i}}{y_i!},
      </men>
      where <m>\lambda_i = e^{\beta_0 + \beta_1 x_{i1} + \cdots + \beta_p x_{ip}}</m>. Taking the log gives the log-likelihood:
      <men xml:id="eq-poisLoglik2">
        \ell(\boldsymbol{\beta}) = \sum_{i=1}^{n} \left[ -\lambda_i + y_i \log(\lambda_i) - \log(y_i!) \right].
      </men>
      Maximum likelihood estimators <m>\hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}</m> are found by maximizing <m>\ell(\boldsymbol{\beta})</m> using iteratively reweighted least squares (IRLS).
      </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="sec-pois-quadratic">
      <title>Second Order Model</title>

      <p>The quadratic model for the Philippines data includes both a linear and squared age term:</p>

      <program language="r" xml:id="code-ch4-quad-model">
        <input>
pois.fit2 &lt;- glm(total ~ age + I(age^2), 
                  family = poisson, data = phil)
summary(pois.fit2)
        </input>
      </program>

      <p>Both the linear and quadratic terms are highly significant. The positive linear coefficient and negative quadratic coefficient capture the inverted-U shape: mean household size increases with age up to a peak and then decreases. This is consistent with the life-cycle pattern of household formation, childbearing, and children leaving home.</p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="sec-pois-addcovariate">
      <title>Adding a Covariate</title>

      <p>We next add region as a covariate, since the EDA showed notable regional variation in household size:</p>

      <program language="r" xml:id="code-ch4-region-model">
        <input>
pois.fit3 &lt;- glm(total ~ age + I(age^2) + region, 
                  family = poisson, data = phil)
summary(pois.fit3)
        </input>
      </program>

      <p>A drop-in-deviance test comparing the model with and without region strongly favors including region as a covariate. After accounting for region, the quadratic pattern with age remains significant.</p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="sec-PoisResid">
      <title>Residuals for Poisson Models</title>

      <p>Two types of residuals are commonly used for Poisson models. The <term>response residuals</term> (also called <term>raw residuals</term>) are the differences between observed and fitted counts:
      <men xml:id="eq-OLSresid">
        e_i = y_i - \hat{\lambda}_i.
      </men>
      The <term>Pearson residuals</term> standardize the raw residuals by dividing by the estimated standard deviation <m>\sqrt{\hat{\lambda}_i}</m>:
      <me>
        r_i = \frac{y_i - \hat{\lambda}_i}{\sqrt{\hat{\lambda}_i}}.
      </me>
      Large absolute values of Pearson residuals indicate observations that are poorly fit by the model.</p>

      <p>Figure <xref ref="fig-resid1"/> shows Pearson residuals plotted against fitted values from the quadratic model with region. The residuals appear roughly symmetric around zero with no strong trend, though some observations are far from zero.</p>

      <figure xml:id="fig-resid1">
        <caption>Pearson residuals vs. fitted values for the Philippines household size Poisson regression model with quadratic age and region.</caption>
        <image source="generated-assets/fig-resid1.png" width="60%">
          <description>Scatterplot of Pearson residuals versus fitted values from the Poisson regression model for Philippines household sizes.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="sec-PoisGOF">
      <title>Goodness-of-Fit</title>

      <p>Goodness-of-fit for a Poisson regression model can be assessed using the residual deviance or the Pearson chi-squared statistic. Under the null hypothesis that the model is correctly specified, the residual deviance (or Pearson chi-squared statistic) follows an approximate chi-squared distribution with degrees of freedom equal to <m>n - p</m>. A large p-value (residual deviance much smaller than df) indicates that the model fits reasonably well.</p>

      <p>For the Philippines quadratic model with region, the residual deviance is 1715.7 on 1480 df (p &lt; .001), suggesting some evidence of lack of fit. This may be because we have not accounted for all relevant predictors or because the Poisson variance assumption is violated.</p>
    </subsection>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-ols-vs-poisson">
    <title>Linear Least Squares vs. Poisson Regression</title>

    <p>Table <xref ref="tab-olsVspois"/> summarizes the key differences between ordinary least squares (OLS) regression and Poisson regression.</p>

    <table xml:id="tab-olsVspois">
      <title>Comparison of OLS and Poisson Regression</title>
      <tabular halign="left" top="major" bottom="major">
        <col width="30%"/>
        <col width="35%"/>
        <col width="35%"/>
        <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
          <cell>Characteristic</cell>
          <cell>OLS Regression</cell>
          <cell>Poisson Regression</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>Response type</cell>
          <cell>Continuous</cell>
          <cell>Count (non-negative integer)</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>Conditional distribution</cell>
          <cell>Normal</cell>
          <cell>Poisson</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>Link function</cell>
          <cell>Identity (<m>\mu = \mathbf{X}\boldsymbol{\beta}</m>)</cell>
          <cell>Log (<m>\log(\lambda) = \mathbf{X}\boldsymbol{\beta}</m>)</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>Mean-variance relationship</cell>
          <cell>Constant variance (<m>\sigma^2</m>)</cell>
          <cell>Mean = variance (<m>\lambda</m>)</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>Parameter estimation</cell>
          <cell>Least squares (closed form)</cell>
          <cell>Maximum likelihood (iterative)</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>Coefficient interpretation</cell>
          <cell>Additive change in mean</cell>
          <cell>Multiplicative change (rate ratio)</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>Inference</cell>
          <cell>t-tests, F-tests</cell>
          <cell>Z-tests, chi-squared tests, drop-in-deviance</cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-cs-campuscrime">
    <title>Case Study: Campus Crime</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>Our second case study examines violent crime on U.S. college and university campuses. Data on 81 schools were collected, including the number of violent crimes reported in 2010, the enrollment, the type of institution (college or university), and the geographic region. We will use Poisson regression with an offset to model the rate of violent crime per 1,000 enrolled students.</p>
    </introduction>

    <subsection xml:id="sec-crime-dataorg">
      <title>Data Organization</title>

      <p>The data set <c>campuscrime10.csv</c> is loaded and new variables are created for the enrollment in thousands and the violent crime rate per 1,000 students:</p>

      <program language="r" xml:id="code-ch4-crime-load">
        <input>
c.data &lt;- read.csv("data/campuscrime10.csv")
c.data &lt;- c.data %&gt;%
  mutate(enroll1000 = enrollment / 1000,
         nvrate = nv / enroll1000)
        </input>
      </program>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="sec-crime-eda">
      <title>Exploratory Data Analysis</title>

      <p>Figure <xref ref="fig-nviolent"/> shows the distribution of violent crime counts. The distribution is right-skewed with one extreme value (a large Southeastern school with a rate of 5.4 violent crimes per 1,000 students). The mean count (8.6) and variance (113.7) are far apart, suggesting potential overdispersion.</p>

      <figure xml:id="fig-nviolent">
        <caption>Histogram of the number of violent crimes reported at 81 U.S. college and university campuses in 2010.</caption>
        <image source="generated-assets/fig-nviolent.png" width="60%">
          <description>Histogram of violent crime counts across campuses, right-skewed with a potential outlier.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <p>The data include two covariates of interest: type of institution and region. In our data, 65% of the 81 schools are universities and 35% are colleges. The proportion of colleges varies from a low of 20% in the Southwest (SW) to a high of 50% in the West (W).</p>

      <p>While a Poisson regression model is a good first choice because the responses are counts per year, the counts are not directly comparable because they come from different size schools. We expect schools with more students to have more reports of violent crime. We therefore examine the violent crime rate per 1,000 enrolled students during the exploratory analysis. Note that there is a noticeable outlier for a Southeastern school (5.4 violent crimes per 1,000 students) and there is an observed rate of 0 for the Southwestern colleges. We combined the SW and SE regions to form a single South category and removed the extreme observation from the data set.</p>

      <figure xml:id="fig-boxtyperegion">
        <caption>Boxplot of violent crime rate per 1,000 students by region and type of institution (colleges (C) on the left, and universities (U) on the right).</caption>
        <image source="generated-assets/fig-boxtyperegion.png" width="60%">
          <description>Side-by-side boxplots of violent crime rate by region and institutional type (college vs. university).</description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <p>Figure <xref ref="fig-boxtyperegion"/> shows that mean violent crime rates are generally lower at colleges within a region (with the exception of the Northeast), and the regional pattern of rates at universities appears to differ from that of the colleges.</p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="sec-crime-offset">
      <title>Accounting for Enrollment</title>

      <p>Although working with observed rates per 1,000 students is useful during the EDA, we do not use these rates explicitly in the model. The counts (per year) are the Poisson responses when modeling, so we must account for differences in enrollment using an <term>offset</term>. <idx>offset</idx>  The offset is the log of the enrollment in thousands, added to the right side of the model with a fixed coefficient of 1:
      <md>
        <mrow>\log\!\left(\frac{\lambda}{\textrm{enroll1000}}\right) \amp= \beta_0 + \beta_1(\textrm{type})</mrow>
        <mrow>\log(\lambda) - \log(\textrm{enroll1000}) \amp= \beta_0 + \beta_1(\textrm{type})</mrow>
        <mrow>\log(\lambda) \amp= \beta_0 + \beta_1(\textrm{type}) + \log(\textrm{enroll1000}).</mrow>
      </md>
      </p>

      <p>While this heuristic is helpful, it is important to note that it is <em>not</em> <m>\lambda/\textrm{enroll1000}</m> that we are modeling. We are still modeling <m>\log(\lambda)</m>, but adding an offset to adjust for differing enrollments, where the offset has the unusual feature that its coefficient is fixed at 1.0. As a result, no estimated coefficient for <c>enroll1000</c> or <m>\log(\textrm{enroll1000})</m> will appear in the output.</p>
    </subsection>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-modeling-assumptions">
    <title>Modeling Assumptions</title>

    <p>In the campus crime data, the variances are greatly higher than the mean counts in almost every group, giving reason to question the Poisson assumption that variability equals the mean. The fact that the variance of the violent crime rate tends to be on the same scale as the mean suggests that adjusting for enrollment may provide some help, although it may not completely solve the issues with excessive variance.</p>

    <p>As for other model assumptions, linearity with respect to <m>\log(\lambda)</m> is difficult to discern without continuous predictors, and independence cannot be assessed without knowing how the schools were selected.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-initial-models">
    <title>Initial Models</title>

    <p>We are interested primarily in differences in violent crime between institutional types controlling for region, so we fit a model with region, institutional type, and the enrollment offset:</p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="code-ch4-main-model">
      <input>
modeltr &lt;- glm(nv ~ type + region, family = poisson,
               offset = log(enroll1000), data = c.data)
coef(summary(modeltr))
cat(" Residual deviance = ", summary(modeltr)$deviance, " on ",
    summary(modeltr)$df.residual, "df", "\n",
    "Dispersion parameter = ", summary(modeltr)$dispersion)
      </input>
    </program>

    <p>From our model, the Northeast and the South differ significantly from the Central region (p = 0.00000037 and p = 0.0000924, respectively). The estimated coefficient of 0.778 means that the violent crime rate per 1,000 in the Northeast is nearly 2.2 (<m>e^{0.778}</m>) times that of the Central region, controlling for the type of school. A Wald-type confidence interval for this factor can be constructed by first calculating a CI for the coefficient (<m>0.778 \pm 1.96 \cdot 0.153</m>) and then exponentiating (1.61 to 2.94).</p>

    <subsection xml:id="sec-tukey-hsd">
      <title>Tukey's Honestly Significant Differences</title>

      <p>Comparisons to regions other than the Central region can be accomplished by changing the reference region. If many comparisons are made, it would be best to adjust for multiple comparisons using a method such as <term>Tukey's Honestly Significant Differences</term>, <idx>Tukey's honestly significant differences</idx> which considers all pairwise comparisons among regions. This method helps control the large number of false positives that would arise from running many independent tests.</p>

      <program language="r" xml:id="code-ch4-tukey">
        <input>
mult_comp &lt;- summary(glht(modeltr, mcp(region = "Tukey")))
tibble(comparison = rownames(mult_comp$linfct),
       estimate   = mult_comp$test$coefficients,
       SE         = mult_comp$test$sigma,
       z_value    = mult_comp$test$tstat,
       p_value    = mult_comp$test$pvalues)
        </input>
      </program>

      <p>We find that the Northeast has significantly higher rates of violent crimes than the Central, Midwest, and Western regions, while the South has significantly higher rates than the Central and Midwest, controlling for the type of institution. The university indicator is significant; after exponentiating the coefficient, we estimate an approximately 32% (<m>e^{0.280}</m>) increase in violent crime rate over colleges after controlling for region.</p>

      <p>These results suggest significant differences in regions and type of institution. However, the EDA findings suggest the effect of the type of institution may vary by region, so we consider a model with an interaction between region and type:</p>

      <program language="r" xml:id="code-ch4-interaction-model">
        <input>
modeli &lt;- glm(nv ~ type + region + region:type,
              family = poisson,
              offset = log(enroll1000), data = c.data)
drop_in_dev &lt;- anova(modeltr, modeli, test = "Chisq")
drop_in_dev
        </input>
      </program>

      <p>The drop-in-deviance test provides convincing evidence of an interaction between region and type of institution (<m>\chi^2 = 71.98</m>, df = 4, p &lt; .001). Our model estimates that violent crime rates are 13.6 (<m>e^{.196+2.411}</m>) times higher in universities in the West compared to colleges, while in the Northeast we estimate that violent crime rates are 2.4 (<m>\frac{1}{e^{.196-1.070}}</m>) times higher in colleges.</p>

      <p>The residual deviance (276.70 with 70 df) suggests significant lack-of-fit in the interaction model (p &lt; .001). In the absence of other covariates or extreme observations, we consider overdispersion as a possible explanation.</p>
    </subsection>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-overdispPois">
    <title>Overdispersion</title>

    <subsection xml:id="sec-dispersion-param">
      <title>Dispersion Parameter Adjustment</title>

      <p><term>Overdispersion</term> <idx>overdispersion</idx> suggests that there is more variation in the response than the model implies. Under a Poisson model, we would expect the means and variances of the response to be about the same in various groups. Without adjusting for overdispersion, we use incorrect, artificially small standard errors, leading to artificially small p-values for model coefficients.</p>

      <p>We can estimate a dispersion parameter, <m>\hat{\phi}</m>, by dividing the sum of squared Pearson residuals by the residual degrees of freedom:
      <me>
        \hat{\phi} = \frac{\sum r_i^2}{n-p},
      </me>
      where <m>r_i</m> are the Pearson residuals. If there is no overdispersion, this estimate should be close to 1. Values greater than 1 indicate overdispersion. We can inflate standard errors by multiplying the variance by <m>\hat{\phi}</m>, giving <term>quasi-Poisson</term> <idx>quasi-Poisson</idx> standard errors: <m>SE_Q(\hat{\beta}) = \sqrt{\hat{\phi}} \cdot SE(\hat{\beta})</m>. This approach is called <term>quasilikelihood</term>. <idx>quasilikelihood</idx></p>

      <program language="r" xml:id="code-ch4-quasipoisson">
        <input>
modeliq &lt;- glm(nv ~ type + region + region:type,
               family = quasipoisson,
               offset = log(enroll1000), data = c.data)
coef(summary(modeliq))
cat(" Residual deviance = ", summary(modeliq)$deviance, " on ",
    summary(modeliq)$df.residual, "df", "\n",
    "Dispersion parameter = ", summary(modeliq)$dispersion)
        </input>
      </program>

      <p>The estimated dispersion parameter is 4.447, much larger than 1.0, confirming overdispersion. The larger estimated standard errors in the quasi-Poisson model reflect this adjustment. For example, the standard error for the West region term from the likelihood approach is 0.7906, whereas the quasilikelihood standard error is <m>\sqrt{4.47} \cdot 0.7906 = 1.6671</m>. This term is no longer significant under the quasi-Poisson model. After adjusting for overdispersion, none of the model coefficients are significant at the 0.05 level, because standard errors were all increased by a factor of 2.1 (<m>\sqrt{\hat{\phi}} = \sqrt{4.447} = 2.1</m>).</p>

      <p>Note that tests for individual parameters are now based on the t-distribution rather than a standard Normal, with test statistic <m>t = \hat{\beta} / SE_Q(\hat{\beta})</m>. Drop-in-deviance tests can similarly be adjusted by dividing the test statistic (per degree of freedom) by the estimated dispersion parameter and comparing the result to an F-distribution: <m>F = \frac{\textrm{drop in deviance} / \textrm{difference in df}}{\hat{\phi}}</m>.</p>

      <program language="r" xml:id="code-ch4-quasi-drop">
        <input>
modeltrq &lt;- glm(nv ~ type + region, family = quasipoisson,
               offset = log(enroll1000), data = c.data)
drop_in_dev &lt;- anova(modeltrq, modeliq, test = "F")
drop_in_dev
        </input>
      </program>

      <p>Even after adjusting for overdispersion, there is still statistically significant evidence (<m>F = 4.05</m>, p = .0052) that the difference between colleges and universities in violent crime rate differs by region.</p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="sec-compTablePois">
      <title>No Dispersion vs. Overdispersion</title>

      <p>Table <xref ref="tab-compTable"/> summarizes the comparison between Poisson inference (assuming no overdispersion) and quasi-Poisson inference (accounting for overdispersion).</p>

      <table xml:id="tab-compTable">
        <title>Comparison of Poisson and quasi-Poisson Inference</title>
        <tabular halign="left" top="major" bottom="major">
          <col width="35%"/>
          <col width="30%"/>
          <col width="35%"/>
          <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
            <cell></cell>
            <cell>Poisson</cell>
            <cell>quasi-Poisson</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>Estimate</cell>
            <cell><m>\hat{\beta}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\hat{\beta}</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>Std error</cell>
            <cell><m>SE(\hat{\beta})</m></cell>
            <cell><m>SE_Q(\hat{\beta}) = \sqrt{\hat{\phi}}\, SE(\hat{\beta})</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>Wald-type test stat</cell>
            <cell><m>Z = \hat{\beta} / SE(\hat{\beta})</m></cell>
            <cell><m>t = \hat{\beta} / SE_Q(\hat{\beta})</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>Confidence interval</cell>
            <cell><m>\hat{\beta} \pm z^* SE(\hat{\beta})</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\hat{\beta} \pm t^* SE_Q(\hat{\beta})</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>Drop-in-deviance test</cell>
            <cell><m>\chi^2 = D(\text{reduced}) - D(\text{full})</m></cell>
            <cell><m>F = (\chi^2 / \Delta\text{df}) / \hat{\phi}</m></cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="sec-negbinom">
      <title>Negative Binomial Modeling</title>

      <p>Another approach to dealing with overdispersion is to model the response using a <term>negative binomial</term> <idx>negative binomial regression</idx> instead of a Poisson distribution. An advantage of this approach is that it introduces an additional parameter beyond <m>\lambda</m>, giving the model more flexibility. Unlike the quasi-Poisson model, the negative binomial model assumes an explicit likelihood, which enables standard model comparison tools.</p>

      <p>Mathematically, the negative binomial model can be thought of as a Poisson model where <m>\lambda</m> is itself random, following a gamma distribution. Specifically, if <m>Y|\lambda \sim \textrm{Poisson}(\lambda)</m> and <m>\lambda \sim \textrm{gamma}(r, \frac{1-p}{p})</m>, then <m>Y \sim \textrm{NegBinom}(r, p)</m> where <m>E(Y) = \mu</m> and <m>\textrm{Var}(Y) = \mu + \mu^2/r</m>. Smaller values of <m>r</m> indicate greater overdispersion.</p>

      <program language="r" xml:id="code-ch4-negbinom">
        <input>
modelinb &lt;- glm.nb(nv ~ type + region + region:type,
               offset(log(enroll1000)), data = c.data)
coef(summary(modelinb))
cat(" Residual deviance = ", summary(modelinb)$deviance, " on ",
    summary(modelinb)$df.residual, "df", "\n",
    "Dispersion parameter (theta) = ", summary(modelinb)$theta)
        </input>
      </program>

      <p>These results differ from the quasi-Poisson model. Several effects are now statistically significant at the 0.05 level: the effect of type of institution for the Central region (<m>Z = 2.64</m>, p = .008), the difference between Northeast and Central regions for colleges (<m>Z = 2.76</m>, p = .006), and the West/Central difference in type effect (<m>Z = 2.71</m>, p = .007). Compared to the quasi-Poisson model, negative binomial coefficient estimates are generally similar in direction and magnitude, but the negative binomial standard errors are somewhat smaller.</p>

      <p>In summary, we explored differences in violent crime rate between colleges and universities, controlling for region. Our initial efforts suggested differences between college and university types with a significant region-by-type interaction. However, this model exhibited significant lack-of-fit. Accounting for lack-of-fit through quasilikelihood and negative binomial regression provided slightly different conclusions. We may want to look for additional covariates and/or more data.</p>
    </subsection>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="cs-drinking">
    <title>Case Study: Weekend Drinking</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>Sometimes when analyzing Poisson data, there are many more zeros than expected for a Poisson random variable. An informal survey of students in an introductory statistics course included the question, <q>How many alcoholic drinks did you consume last weekend?</q> This survey was conducted on a dry campus where no alcohol is officially allowed, so some respondents never drink. These non-drinkers would always report zero drinks. However, there are also students who are drinkers reporting zero drinks because they simply did not happen to drink the past weekend. Our zeros are a <term>mixture</term> of responses from non-drinkers and drinkers who abstained. Ideally, we would like to sort out non-drinkers from drinkers when performing our analysis.</p>
    </introduction>

    <subsection xml:id="sec-drinking-rq">
      <title>Research Question</title>

      <p>The purpose of this survey is to explore factors related to drinking behavior on a dry campus. What proportion of students on this dry campus never drink? What factors, such as off-campus living and sex, are related to whether students drink? Among those who do drink, to what extent is moving off campus associated with the number of drinks in a weekend? These questions would be simple to answer if we knew who was and was not a drinker in our sample. Unfortunately, the non-drinkers did not identify themselves as such, so we need a model that allows us to estimate the proportion of drinkers and non-drinkers.</p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="sec-drinking-dataorg">
      <title>Data Organization</title>

      <p>Each line of <c>weekendDrinks.csv</c> contains data from a student in an introductory statistics course. The response is <c>drinks</c>, the number of alcoholic drinks consumed the previous weekend. Predictors include whether the student lives <c>off.campus</c>, <c>sex</c>, and whether the student is likely a <c>firstYear</c> student based on dorm assignment:</p>

      <program language="r" xml:id="code-ch4-drinking-load">
        <input>
zip.data &lt;- read.csv("data/weekendDrinks.csv")
zip.data &lt;- zip.data %&gt;%
  mutate(off.campus = ifelse(dorm == "off campus", 1, 0),
         firstYear  = ifelse(dorm %in% c("Smiley","Nyland","Olin",
                                         "Bohn","Mohn","New"), 1, 0))
head(zip.data)
        </input>
      </program>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="sec-drinking-eda">
      <title>Exploratory Data Analysis</title>

      <p>About 47% of the 77 respondents reported zero drinks last weekend. A Poisson distribution with the observed mean of 2.08 drinks would predict only about 12% zeros. This dramatic excess of zeros motivates a zero-inflated model.</p>

      <figure xml:id="fig-obsVmodel">
        <caption>Observed proportions of weekend drink counts (left) vs. proportions predicted by a Poisson model with mean 2.08 (right). The observed data have far more zeros than the Poisson model predicts.</caption>
        <image source="generated-assets/fig-obsVmodel.png" width="70%">
          <description>Two bar charts comparing observed frequencies of weekend drinks to Poisson model predictions, showing excess zeros in the observed data.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="sec-zip-model">
      <title>Zero-Inflated Poisson Model</title>

      <p>A <term>zero-inflated Poisson (ZIP)</term> <idx>zero-inflated Poisson (ZIP)</idx> model assumes that zeros arise from two sources: (1) structural zeros from true non-drinkers who would always report zero, and (2) sampling zeros from drinkers who happened to abstain during the past weekend. The model has two components:</p>

      <p><ul>
        <li><p>A <em>binary</em> component to classify students as non-drinkers (structural zeros) or potential drinkers, using logistic regression with predictors like <c>firstYear</c>.</p></li>
        <li><p>A <em>Poisson count</em> component to model the number of drinks among potential drinkers, using predictors like <c>off.campus</c> and <c>sex</c>.</p></li>
      </ul></p>

      <p>Let <m>\alpha</m> denote the probability that a student is a non-drinker (structural zero). Then:
      <me>
        P(Y = 0) = \alpha + (1 - \alpha) e^{-\lambda}
      </me>
      <me>
        P(Y = y) = (1 - \alpha) \frac{e^{-\lambda} \lambda^y}{y!} \quad \text{for } y = 1, 2, 3, \ldots
      </me>
      </p>

      <p>We first fit an ordinary Poisson model, then a ZIP model:</p>

      <program language="r" xml:id="code-ch4-zip-fit">
        <input>
# Ordinary Poisson model
pois.m1 &lt;- glm(drinks ~ off.campus + sex, 
               family = poisson, data = zip.data)

# Zero-inflated Poisson model
zip.m2 &lt;- zeroinfl(drinks ~ off.campus + sex | firstYear,
                   data = zip.data)
summary(zip.m2)
        </input>
      </program>

      <p>The ZIP model output contains two sets of coefficients: count model coefficients (Poisson part) and zero-inflation model coefficients (binary part). We exponentiate coefficients for ease of interpretation:</p>

      <program language="r" xml:id="code-ch4-zip-coef">
        <input>
exp(coef(zip.m2))
        </input>
      </program>

      <p>Considering the <q>Count model coefficients,</q> which provide information on how the sex and off-campus status of a drinker relate to the number of drinks: for those who drink, the average number of drinks for males is <m>e^{1.0209} = 2.76</m> times the number for females (<m>Z = 5.827</m>, p &lt; 0.001), given that both students live in comparable settings. Among drinkers, the mean number of drinks for students living off campus is <m>e^{0.4159} = 1.52</m> times that of students living on campus for those of the same sex (<m>Z = 2.021</m>, p = 0.0433).</p>

      <p>The <q>Zero-inflation model coefficients</q> refer to separating drinkers from non-drinkers. An important consideration is whether a student is a first-year student. We have
      <me>
        \log\!\left(\frac{\alpha}{1-\alpha}\right) = -0.6036 + 1.1364 \cdot \textrm{firstYear}.
      </me>
      </p>

      <p>Exponentiating the coefficient for the first-year term yields 3.12. This is interpreted as: the odds (<m>\alpha/(1-\alpha)</m>) that a first-year student is a non-drinker are 3.12 times the odds that an upper-class student is a non-drinker. Solving for <m>\alpha</m>, we get
      <me>
        \hat{\alpha} = \frac{e^{-0.6036 + 1.1364\,(\textrm{firstYear})}}{1 + e^{-0.6036 + 1.1364\,(\textrm{firstYear})}}.
      </me>
      </p>

      <p>The estimated probability that a first-year student is a non-drinker is
      <me>
        \frac{e^{0.533}}{1 + e^{0.533}} = 0.630,
      </me>
      or 63.0%, while for non-first-year students, the estimated probability of being a non-drinker is 0.354. This transformation (logistic) is the same one used to estimate probabilities in logistic regression, which we discuss in <xref ref="ch-logreg"/>.</p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="sec-vuong-test">
      <title>The Vuong Test (optional)</title>

      <p>Moving from ordinary Poisson to zero-inflated Poisson has helped us address additional research questions. While a ZIP model seems more faithful to the nature and structure of this data, can we quantitatively show that a ZIP is better than an ordinary Poisson model? We cannot use the drop-in-deviance test because these two models are not nested. <xref ref="Vuong1989"/> devised a test to compare predicted probabilities of <term>non-nested</term> models. Essentially, the <term>Vuong test</term> <idx>Vuong test</idx> can compare a zero-inflated model and an ordinary regression model.</p>

      <program language="r" xml:id="code-ch4-vuong">
        <input>
vuong(pois.m1, zip.m2)
        </input>
      </program>

      <p>The Vuong test compares Model 1 (ordinary Poisson) to Model 2 (ZIP). If the two models do not differ, the test statistic is asymptotically standard Normal with a large p-value. Here the test indicates that the zero-inflation model is better (<m>Z = -2.69</m>, p = .0036). Note that the test depends on sufficiently large <m>n</m> for the Normal approximation, so since our sample size (n = 77) is somewhat small, we interpret this result with caution.</p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="sec-drinking-residuals">
      <title>Residual Plot</title>

      <p>Fitted values (<m>\hat{y}</m>) and residuals (<m>y - \hat{y}</m>) can be computed for zero-inflation models and plotted. Figure <xref ref="fig-poisRes"/> reveals that one observation appears to be extreme (<m>Y = 22</m> drinks during the past weekend). It might be worthwhile to get a sense of how influential this extreme observation is by removing <m>Y = 22</m> and refitting the model.</p>

      <figure xml:id="fig-poisRes">
        <caption>Residuals by fitted counts for ZIP model. One observation (<m>Y=22</m>) appears extreme.</caption>
        <image source="generated-assets/fig-poisRes.png" width="60%">
          <description>Scatterplot of residuals versus fitted values from the ZIP model, with one extreme point at Y=22 labeled.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <program language="r" xml:id="code-ch4-resid-zip">
        <input>
res.df &lt;- data.frame(resid = residuals(zip.m2), 
                     fit   = fitted(zip.m2))
ggplot(res.df, aes(x = fit, y = resid)) +
  geom_point() +
  ylab("Residuals from ZIP model") +
  xlab("Fitted values from ZIP model") +
  annotate("text", x = 4.2, y = 5.3, label = "Y=22")
        </input>
      </program>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="sec-drinking-limitations">
      <title>Limitations</title>

      <p>The weekend drinking survey question should raise several red flags. What time period constitutes the <q>weekend</q>? Some students may think of only Saturday night, while others include Friday night or Sunday evening. What constitutes a drink---a bottle of beer? How many drinks will a respondent report for a bottle of wine? Precise definitions would vastly improve data quality. There is also an issue related to confidentiality: if the data are collected in class, will the teacher be able to identify the respondent? Will respondents worry that a particular response will affect their grade or lead to repercussions on a dry campus?</p>

      <p>In addition, there are concerns about whether this data represents a random sample of any population (it does not), and the sample size (n = 77) is not impressively large for ZIP models. ZIP models are becoming increasingly common---they demonstrate that modeling can be flexible and creative, a theme throughout this book.</p>
    </subsection>
  </section>

  <exercises xml:id="exer-ch4">
    <title>Exercises</title>

    <subexercises xml:id="exer-ch4-conceptual">
      <title>Conceptual Exercises</title>

      <introduction>
        <p>Exercises 1&#8211;4 involve predicting a <term>response</term> using one or more <term>explanatory variables</term>, where the response variables are counts per some unit of time or space. List the response (both what is being counted and over what unit of time or space) and the relevant explanatory variables.</p>
      </introduction>

      <exercise xml:id="exer-ch4-c1">
        <statement>
          <p>Are the number of motorcycle deaths in a given year related to a state's helmet laws?</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="exer-ch4-c2">
        <statement>
          <p>Does the number of employers conducting on-campus interviews during a year differ for public and private colleges?</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="exer-ch4-c3">
        <statement>
          <p>Does the daily number of asthma-related visits to an Emergency Room differ depending on air pollution indices?</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="exer-ch4-c4">
        <statement>
          <p>Has the number of deformed fish in randomly selected Minnesota lakes been affected by changes in trace minerals in the water over the last decade?</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="exer-ch4-c5">
        <statement>
          <p>Models of the form <m>Y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_i + \epsilon_i</m>, <m>\epsilon_i \overset{\text{i.i.d.}}{\sim} N(0,\sigma)</m> are fit using the method of least squares. What method is used to fit Poisson regression models?</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="exer-ch4-c6">
        <statement>
          <p>What should be done before adjusting for overdispersion?</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="exer-ch4-c7">
        <statement>
          <p>Why are quasi-Poisson models used, and how do the results typically compare for corresponding models using regular Poisson regression?</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="exer-ch4-c8">
        <statement>
          <p>Why is the log of mean counts, <m>\log(\bar{Y})</m>, not <m>\bar{Y}</m>, plotted against <m>X</m> when assessing the assumptions for Poisson regression?</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="exer-ch4-c9">
        <statement>
          <p>How can the assumption of <em>mean = variance</em> be checked for Poisson regression? What if there are not many repeated observations at each level of <m>X</m>?</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="exer-ch4-c10">
        <statement>
          <p>Is it possible that a predictor is significant for a model fit using Poisson regression, but not for a model for the same data fit using quasi-Poisson regression? Explain.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <introduction>
        <p>Complete (a)&#8211;(d) in the context of the study for Exercises 11&#8211;13.</p>
        <p><ol label="a">
          <li><p>Define the response.</p></li>
          <li><p>What are the possible values for the response?</p></li>
          <li><p>What does <m>\lambda</m> represent?</p></li>
          <li><p>Would a zero-inflated model be considered here? If so, what would be a <q>true zero</q>?</p></li>
        </ol></p>
      </introduction>

      <exercise xml:id="exer-ch4-c11">
        <title>Fish (or, as they say in French, poisson)</title>
        <statement>
          <p>A state wildlife biologist collected data from 250 park visitors as they left at the end of their stay. Each was asked to report the number of fish they caught during their one-week stay. On average, visitors caught 21.5 fish per week.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="exer-ch4-c12">
        <title>Methadone program recidivism</title>
        <statement>
          <p>Program facilitators keep track of the number of times their program's patients relapse within five years of initial treatment. Data on 100 patients yielded a mean number of 2.8 relapses per patient within the five years of initial treatment.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="exer-ch4-c13">
        <title>Clutch size</title>
        <statement>
          <p>Thirty nests were located and the number of eggs in each nest were counted at the start of a season. Later in the season following a particularly destructive storm, the mean clutch size of the 30 nests was only 1.7 eggs per nest.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="exer-ch4-c14">
        <title>Credit card use</title>
        <statement>
          <p>A survey of 1,000 consumers asked respondents how many credit cards they use. Interest centers on the relationship between credit card use and income, in $10,000. The estimated coefficient for income is 2.1.</p>
          <p><ul>
            <li><p>Identify the predictor and interpret the estimated coefficient for the predictor in this context.</p></li>
            <li><p>Describe how the assumption of linearity can be assessed in this example.</p></li>
            <li><p>Suggest a way in which to assess the equal mean and variance assumption.</p></li>
          </ul></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="exer-ch4-c15">
        <title>Dating online</title>
        <statement>
          <p>Researchers are interested in the number of dates respondents arranged online and whether the rates differ by age group. Each survey respondent was asked how many dates they have arranged online in the past 3 months as well as the typical amount of time, <m>t</m>, in hours, they spend online weekly. Some rows of data appear in Table <xref ref="tab-ch4-dating"/>.</p>

          <table xml:id="tab-ch4-dating">
            <title>Sample data for Exercise 15 (dating online)</title>
            <tabular halign="center" top="major" bottom="major">
              <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
                <cell>Age</cell>
                <cell>Time Online (hrs)</cell>
                <cell>Number of Dates Arranged Online</cell>
              </row>
              <row><cell>19</cell><cell>35</cell><cell>3</cell></row>
              <row><cell>29</cell><cell>20</cell><cell>5</cell></row>
              <row><cell>38</cell><cell>15</cell><cell>0</cell></row>
              <row><cell>55</cell><cell>10</cell><cell>0</cell></row>
            </tabular>
          </table>

          <p><ul>
            <li><p>Identify the response, predictor, and offset in this context. Does using an offset make sense?</p></li>
            <li><p>Write out a model for this data. As part of your model description, define the parameter <m>\lambda</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Consider a zero-inflated Poisson model for this data. Describe what the <q>true zeros</q> would be in this setting.</p></li>
          </ul></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="exer-ch4-c16">
        <title>Poisson approximation: rare events</title>
        <statement>
          <p>For rare diseases, the probability of a case occurring, <m>p</m>, in a very large population, <m>n</m>, is small. With a small <m>p</m> and large <m>n</m>, the random variable <m>Y</m> = the number of cases out of <m>n</m> people can be approximated using a Poisson random variable with <m>\lambda = np</m>. Poisson regression can take into account differences in population sizes, <m>n_i</m>, using as an offset <m>\log(n_i)</m>, as well as differences in a population characteristic like <m>x_i</m>. Thus the model has the form: <m>\log(\lambda_i) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_i + \log(n_i)</m>, where <m>Y_i \sim \textrm{Poisson}(\lambda_i = n_i p_i)</m>.</p>

          <p>Scotto et al. (1974) wondered if skin cancer rates by age group differ by city. Based on their data in Table <xref ref="tab-ch4-skincancer"/>, identify and describe the following quantities:</p>

          <table xml:id="tab-ch4-skincancer">
            <title>Data on the number of cases of non-melanoma skin cancer for women by age group in two metropolitan areas (Minneapolis-St. Paul and Dallas-Ft. Worth)</title>
            <tabular halign="center" top="major" bottom="major">
              <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
                <cell>Number of Cases</cell>
                <cell>Population</cell>
                <cell>Age Group</cell>
                <cell>City</cell>
              </row>
              <row><cell>1</cell><cell>172675</cell><cell>15&#8211;24</cell><cell>1</cell></row>
              <row><cell>16</cell><cell>123065</cell><cell>25&#8211;34</cell><cell>1</cell></row>
              <row><cell>&#8230;</cell><cell>&#8230;</cell><cell>&#8230;</cell><cell>&#8230;</cell></row>
              <row><cell>226</cell><cell>29007</cell><cell>75&#8211;84</cell><cell>2</cell></row>
              <row><cell>65</cell><cell>7538</cell><cell>85+</cell><cell>2</cell></row>
            </tabular>
          </table>
          <p>Note: City 1 = Minneapolis-St. Paul; City 2 = Dallas-Ft. Worth.</p>

          <p><ul>
            <li><p>A case,</p></li>
            <li><p>The population size, <m>n_i</m>,</p></li>
            <li><p>Probability, <m>p_i</m>,</p></li>
            <li><p>Poisson parameter, <m>\lambda_i</m>,</p></li>
            <li><p>Poisson random variables, <m>Y_i</m>, and</p></li>
            <li><p>The predictors, <m>X_i</m>.</p></li>
          </ul></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subexercises>

    <subexercises xml:id="exer-ch4-guided">
      <title>Guided Exercises</title>

      <exercise xml:id="exer-ch4-g1">
        <title>College burglaries</title>
        <statement>
          <p>We wish to build a regression model to describe the number of burglaries on a college campus in a year. Our population of interest will be U.S. liberal arts colleges.</p>
          <p><ol label="a">
            <li><p>Describe why the response variable (<m>Y</m> = # burglaries on campus in a year) could be modeled by a Poisson distribution.</p></li>
            <li><p>Describe explanatory variables which might explain differences in <m>\lambda_i</m> = mean number of burglaries per year on campus <m>i</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Consider a campus with an average of 5 burglaries per year. Use <c>dpois()</c> to sketch a plot of the distribution of <m>Y</m> for this campus. Use <c>rpois()</c> to verify that both the mean and variance of <m>Y</m> are given by <m>\lambda = 5</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Consider a campus with an average of 20 burglaries per year and repeat (c).</p></li>
          </ol></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="exer-ch4-g2">
        <title>Elephant mating</title>
        <statement>
          <p>How does age affect male elephant mating patterns? An article by Poole (1989) investigated whether mating success in male elephants increases with age and whether there is a peak age for mating success. To address this question, the research team followed 41 elephants for one year and recorded both their ages and their number of matings. The data is found in <c>elephant.csv</c>, and the variables are:</p>
          <p><ul>
            <li><p><c>MATINGS</c> = the number of matings in a given year</p></li>
            <li><p><c>AGE</c> = the age of the elephant in years.</p></li>
          </ul></p>
          <p><ol label="a">
            <li><p>Create a histogram of <c>MATINGS</c>. Is there preliminary evidence that number of matings could be modeled as a Poisson response? Explain.</p></li>
            <li><p>Plot <c>MATINGS</c> by <c>AGE</c>. Add a least squares line. Is there evidence that modeling matings using a linear regression with age might not be appropriate? Explain. (Hints: fit a smoother; check residual plots).</p></li>
            <li><p>For each age, calculate the mean number of matings. Take the log of each mean and plot it by <c>AGE</c>.
              <ol label="i">
                <li><p>What assumption can be assessed with this plot?</p></li>
                <li><p>Is there evidence of a quadratic trend on this plot?</p></li>
              </ol>
            </p></li>
            <li><p>Fit a Poisson regression model with a linear term for <c>AGE</c>. Exponentiate and then interpret the coefficient for <c>AGE</c>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Construct a 95% confidence interval for the slope and interpret in context (you may want to exponentiate the endpoints).</p></li>
            <li><p>Are the number of matings significantly related to age? Test with
              <ol label="i">
                <li><p>a Wald test and</p></li>
                <li><p>a drop-in-deviance test.</p></li>
              </ol>
            </p></li>
            <li><p>Add a quadratic term in <c>AGE</c> to determine whether there is a maximum age for the number of matings for elephants. Is a quadratic model preferred to a linear model? Use
              <ol label="i">
                <li><p>a Wald test and</p></li>
                <li><p>a drop-in-deviance test.</p></li>
              </ol>
            </p></li>
            <li><p>What can we say about the goodness-of-fit of the model with age as the sole predictor? Compare the residual deviance for the linear model to a <m>\chi^2</m> distribution with the residual model degrees of freedom.</p></li>
            <li><p>Fit the linear model using quasi-Poisson regression. (Why?)
              <ol label="i">
                <li><p>How do the estimated coefficients change?</p></li>
                <li><p>How do the standard errors change?</p></li>
                <li><p>What is the estimated dispersion parameter?</p></li>
                <li><p>An estimated dispersion parameter greater than 1 suggests overdispersion. When adjusting for overdispersion, are you more or less likely to obtain a significant result when testing coefficients? Why?</p></li>
              </ol>
            </p></li>
          </ol></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="exer-ch4-g3">
        <title>Smoking at work and home</title>
        <statement>
          <p>An earlier study examined the effect of workplace rules in Minnesota which require smokers to smoke cigarettes outside. The number of cigarettes smoked by smokers in a 2-hour period was recorded, along with whether the smoker was at home or at work. A (very) small subset of the data appears in Table <xref ref="tab-ch4-smoking"/>.</p>

          <table xml:id="tab-ch4-smoking">
            <title>A small subset of hypothetical data on Minnesota workplace rules on smoking. X is 0 for home and 1 for work; Y is number of cigarettes in a 2-hour period.</title>
            <tabular halign="center" top="major" bottom="major">
              <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
                <cell>Subject</cell>
                <cell>X (location)</cell>
                <cell>Y (cigarettes)</cell>
              </row>
              <row><cell>1</cell><cell>0</cell><cell>3</cell></row>
              <row><cell>2</cell><cell>1</cell><cell>0</cell></row>
              <row><cell>3</cell><cell>1</cell><cell>0</cell></row>
              <row><cell>4</cell><cell>1</cell><cell>1</cell></row>
              <row><cell>5</cell><cell>0</cell><cell>2</cell></row>
              <row><cell>6</cell><cell>0</cell><cell>1</cell></row>
            </tabular>
          </table>

          <p>Three models are defined as follows:</p>
          <p><ul>
            <li><p>Model 1: Assume that <m>Y \sim \textrm{Poisson}(\lambda)</m>; there is no difference between home and work.</p></li>
            <li><p>Model 2: Assume that <m>Y \sim \textrm{Poisson}(\lambda_W)</m> when the smoker is at work, and <m>Y \sim \textrm{Poisson}(\lambda_H)</m> when the smoker is at home.</p></li>
            <li><p>Model 3: Assume that <m>Y \sim \textrm{Poisson}(\lambda)</m> and <m>\log(\lambda) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X</m>.</p></li>
          </ul></p>
          <p><ol label="a">
            <li><p>Write out the likelihood <m>L(\lambda)</m> and the log-likelihood <m>\log L(\lambda)</m> in Model 1. Use the data values above, and simplify where possible.</p></li>
            <li><p>Intuitively, what would be a reasonable estimate for <m>\lambda</m> based on this data? Why?</p></li>
            <li><p>Find the maximum likelihood estimator for <m>\lambda</m> in Model 1 using an optimization routine in R (but not the <c>glm()</c> function). Use R to produce a plot of the likelihood function <m>L(\lambda)</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Write out the log-likelihood function <m>\log L(\lambda_W, \lambda_H)</m> in Model 2. Use the data values above, and simplify where possible.</p></li>
            <li><p>Intuitively, what would be reasonable estimates for <m>\lambda_W</m> and <m>\lambda_H</m> based on this data? Why?</p></li>
            <li><p>Find the maximum likelihood estimators for <m>\lambda_W</m> and <m>\lambda_H</m> in Model 2 using an optimization routine in R (but not the <c>glm()</c> function).</p></li>
          </ol></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="exer-ch4-g4">
        <title>Smoking at work and home (continued)</title>
        <statement>
          <p>We will use the same data set as in Exercise 3 (Table <xref ref="tab-ch4-smoking"/>).</p>
          <p><ol label="a">
            <li><p>Write out the log-likelihood function <m>\log L(\beta_0, \beta_1)</m> in Model 3. Again, use the data values above, and simplify where possible.</p></li>
            <li><p>Find the maximum likelihood estimators for <m>\beta_0</m> and <m>\beta_1</m> in Model 3 using an optimization routine in R (but not the <c>glm()</c> function). Use R to produce a 3D plot of the log-likelihood function.</p></li>
            <li><p>Confirm your estimates for Model 1 and Model 3 using <c>glm()</c>. Then show that the MLEs for Model 3 agree with the MLEs for Model 2.</p></li>
          </ol></p>
          <p>For the remaining questions, we will focus exclusively on Model 3.</p>
          <p><ol label="d">
            <li><p>State a (one-sided) hypothesis for <m>\beta_1</m> in the context of the problem. Note: we will nevertheless use two-sided tests and intervals in the following questions.</p></li>
            <li><p>Do we need to include an offset in our Poisson regression model? Why or why not?</p></li>
            <li><p>Give estimates of <m>\beta_0</m> and <m>\beta_1</m>, and provide interpretations for both in the context of the problem.</p></li>
            <li><p>Provide and interpret a 95% confidence interval for <m>\beta_1</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Provide two different significance tests for <m>\beta_1</m>, in each case providing a test statistic, a p-value, and a conclusion in the context of the problem.</p></li>
            <li><p>Provide a goodness-of-fit test for Model 3, again providing a test statistic, p-value, and conclusion in context.</p></li>
            <li><p>Can we generalize results of this study to all Minnesota smokers? Why or why not?</p></li>
            <li><p>Can we claim that rules restricting smoking in the workplace have caused lower levels of smoking at work? Explain.</p></li>
            <li><p>Give two ways in which this study might be improved (besides simply <q>bigger sample size</q>).</p></li>
          </ol></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="exer-ch4-g5">
        <title>Campus crime</title>
        <statement>
          <p>The data set <c>campuscrime09.csv</c> contains the number of burglaries reported at a collection of 47 U.S. public universities with over 10,000 students in the year 2009. In addition, covariates are included which may explain differences in crime rates, including total number of students, percentage of men, average SAT and ACT test scores, and tuition.</p>
          <p><ol label="a">
            <li><p>Perform an exploratory data analysis. Support your analysis with plots and summary statistics.
              <ol label="i">
                <li><p>Analyze whether number of burglaries could be reasonably modeled with a Poisson distribution.</p></li>
                <li><p>Analyze which covariates you expect to be the best predictors of burglaries.</p></li>
              </ol>
            </p></li>
            <li><p>Consider a model with 4 predictors: <c>act.comp + tuition + pct.male + total</c>. Try fitting a linear regression with <c>burg09</c> as the response. Are there any concerns with this linear regression model?</p></li>
            <li><p>Run a Poisson regression model with the 4 predictors from (b). Interpret the coefficients for <c>tuition</c> and <c>pct.male</c>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Replace <c>tuition</c> with tuition in thousands in your model from (c). How does your new model compare to your model in (c)? Interpret the coefficient for <c>tuition.thous</c>.</p></li>
            <li><p>We will consider the possibility of including the total number of students at a university as an offset.
              <ol label="i">
                <li><p>Explain why we might consider <c>total</c> as an offset.</p></li>
                <li><p>Refit your model from (d) with <c>log(total)</c> as an offset rather than as a predictor. Does this new model appear to fit better or worse than the model from (d)?</p></li>
                <li><p>Refit your model from (d) with <c>log(total)</c> rather than <c>total</c> as a predictor. If total were a good candidate for an offset, what would we expect the coefficient of <c>log(total)</c> to be? Does a 95% confidence interval for that coefficient contain the value you expected?</p></li>
              </ol>
            </p></li>
            <li><p>Run the following model, then interpret the coefficients for <c>tuition.thous</c> and the interaction between <c>tuition.thous</c> and <c>act.comp</c>.</p>
            <program language="r" xml:id="code-ch4-g5-model">
              <input>
crime &lt;- mutate(crime, total.thous = total/1000)
fit3 &lt;- glm(burg09 ~ act.comp + tuition.thous +
            total.thous + act.comp:tuition.thous +
            act.comp:total.thous, family = poisson,
            data = crime)
              </input>
            </program>
            </li>
          </ol></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="exer-ch4-g6">
        <title>U.S. National Medical Expenditure Survey</title>
        <statement>
          <p>The data set <c>NMES1988</c> in the <c>AER</c> package contains a sample of individuals over 65 who are covered by Medicare, collected to assess the demand for health care through physician office visits, outpatient visits, ER visits, hospital stays, etc. The data can be accessed by installing and loading the <c>AER</c> package and then running <c>data(NMES1988)</c>.</p>
          <p><ol label="a">
            <li><p>Show through graphical means that there are more respondents with 0 <c>visits</c> than might be expected under a Poisson model.</p></li>
            <li><p>Fit a ZIP model for the number of physician office <c>visits</c> using <c>chronic</c>, <c>health</c>, and <c>insurance</c> as predictors for the Poisson count, and <c>chronic</c> and <c>insurance</c> as the predictors for the binary part of the model. Then, provide interpretations in context for the following model parameters:
              <ul>
                <li><p><c>chronic</c> in the Poisson part of the model</p></li>
                <li><p>poor <c>health</c> in the Poisson part of the model</p></li>
                <li><p>the Intercept in the logistic part of the model</p></li>
                <li><p><c>insurance</c> in the logistic part of the model</p></li>
              </ul>
            </p></li>
            <li><p>Is there significant evidence that the ZIP model is an improvement over a simple Poisson regression model?</p></li>
          </ol></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="exer-ch4-g7">
        <title>Going vague: ambiguity in political issue statements</title>
        <statement>
          <p>In this exercise, you will use a <term>hurdle model</term> <idx>hurdle model</idx> to analyze the data. A hurdle model is similar to a zero-inflated Poisson model, but instead of assuming that <q>zeros</q> are comprised of two distinct groups (those who would always be 0 and those who happen to be 0), the hurdle model assumes that <q>zeros</q> are a single entity. Therefore, in a hurdle model, cases are either <q>zeros</q> or <q>non-zeros</q>, where <q>non-zeros</q> <em>hurdle</em> the 0 threshold and must always have counts of 1 or above. We will use the <c>pscl</c> package and the <c>hurdle</c> function.</p>

          <p>In a 2018 study, Chapp (2018) scraped every issue statement from webpages of candidates for the U.S. House of Representatives, counting the number of issues candidates commented on and scoring the level of ambiguity of each statement. The data set <c>ambiguity.csv</c> contains:</p>
          <p><ul>
            <li><p><c>name</c>: candidate name</p></li>
            <li><p><c>distID</c>: unique identification number for Congressional district</p></li>
            <li><p><c>ideology</c>: candidate left-right orientation</p></li>
            <li><p><c>democrat</c>: 1 if Democrat, 0 if Republican</p></li>
            <li><p><c>mismatch</c>: disagreement between candidate ideology and district voter ideology</p></li>
            <li><p><c>incumbent</c>: 1 if incumbent, 0 if not</p></li>
            <li><p><c>demHeterogeneity</c>: how much voters in a district differ according to race, education, occupation, etc.</p></li>
            <li><p><c>attHeterogeneity</c>: how much voters in a district differ according to political ideology</p></li>
            <li><p><c>distLean</c>: overall ideological lean in a district</p></li>
            <li><p><c>totalIssuePages</c>: number of issues candidates commented on (response)</p></li>
          </ul></p>
          <p><ol label="a">
            <li><p>Create a frequency plot of <c>totalIssuePages</c>. Why might we consider using a hurdle model compared to a Poisson model? Why can't we use a zero-inflated Poisson model?</p></li>
            <li><p>Create a plot of the empirical log odds of having at least one issue statement by ideology. You may want to group ideology values first. What can you conclude from this plot? (See <xref ref="ch-logreg"/> for more details.)</p></li>
            <li><p>Create a scatterplot showing the log of the mean number of issues vs. ideology group by party, among candidates with at least one issue statement. What can we conclude from this plot?</p></li>
            <li><p>Create a hurdle model with <c>ideology</c> and <c>democrat</c> as predictors in both parts. Interpret <c>ideology</c> in both parts of the model.</p></li>
            <li><p>Repeat (d), but include an interaction in both parts. Interpret the interaction in the zero hurdle part of the model.</p></li>
            <li><p>Find the best model you can to determine <c>totalIssuePages</c>. Write a short paragraph discussing implications of your model.</p></li>
          </ol></p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subexercises>

    <subexercises xml:id="exer-ch4-openended">
      <title>Open-Ended Exercises</title>

      <exercise xml:id="exer-ch4-oe1">
        <title>Airbnb in NYC</title>
        <statement>
          <p>Awad (2017) scraped 40,628 Airbnb listings from New York City in March 2017 and assembled the data set <c>NYCairbnb.csv</c>. Key variables include:</p>
          <p><ul>
            <li><p><c>id</c>: unique ID number for each unit</p></li>
            <li><p><c>last_scraped</c>: date when information was scraped</p></li>
            <li><p><c>host_since</c>: date when host first listed the unit on Airbnb</p></li>
            <li><p><c>days</c>: <c>last_scraped</c> <m>-</m> <c>host_since</c> = number of days the unit has been listed</p></li>
            <li><p><c>room_type</c>: Entire home/apt., Private room, or Shared room</p></li>
            <li><p><c>bathrooms</c>: number of bathrooms</p></li>
            <li><p><c>bedrooms</c>: number of bedrooms</p></li>
            <li><p><c>price</c>: price per night (dollars)</p></li>
            <li><p><c>number_of_reviews</c>: number of reviews for the unit on Airbnb</p></li>
            <li><p><c>review_scores_cleanliness</c>: cleanliness score from reviews (1&#8211;10)</p></li>
            <li><p><c>review_scores_location</c>: location score from reviews (1&#8211;10)</p></li>
            <li><p><c>review_scores_value</c>: value score from reviews (1&#8211;10)</p></li>
            <li><p><c>instant_bookable</c>: <q>t</q> if instantly bookable, <q>f</q> if not</p></li>
          </ul></p>
          <p>Perform an EDA, build a model, and interpret model coefficients to describe variation in the number of reviews (a proxy for the number of rentals, which is not available) as a function of the variables provided. Don't forget to consider an offset, if needed.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="exer-ch4-oe2">
        <title>Crab satellites</title>
        <statement>
          <p>Brockmann (1996) carried out a study of nesting female horseshoe crabs. Female horseshoe crabs often have male crabs attached to a female's nest, known as <term>satellites</term>. One objective of the study was to determine which characteristics of the female were associated with the number of satellites. The data can be found in <c>crab.csv</c> and includes:</p>
          <p><ul>
            <li><p><c>NumSat</c>: number of satellites</p></li>
            <li><p><c>Width</c>: carapace width (cm)</p></li>
            <li><p><c>Wt</c>: weight (kg)</p></li>
            <li><p><c>Sp</c>: spine condition (1 = both good, 2 = one worn or broken, 3 = both worn or broken)</p></li>
            <li><p><c>C</c>: color (1 = light medium, 2 = medium, 3 = dark medium, 4 = dark)</p></li>
          </ul></p>
          <p>Use Poisson regression to investigate the research question. Be sure you work to obtain an appropriate model before considering overdispersion. Should a hurdle model be considered here? If so, fit a hurdle model and interpret in context.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="exer-ch4-oe3">
        <title>Doctor visits</title>
        <statement>
          <p>Data was collected on doctor visits from a sample of 5,190 people in the 1977/1978 Australian Health Survey. Cameron (1986) sought to explain the variation in doctor visits using one or more explanatory variables. The data can be found in an R data set from <c>library(AER)</c> accessible with the command <c>data("DoctorVisits")</c>. Variable descriptions can be found under <c>help("DoctorVisits")</c>.</p>
          <p>Explore the use of a zero-inflated model for this data. Begin with a histogram of the number of visits, complete an EDA, and then fit several models. Summarize your results.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise xml:id="exer-ch4-oe4">
        <title>More fish</title>
        <statement>
          <p>The number of fish caught (<c>count</c>), persons in the party (<c>persons</c>), the number of children in the party (<c>child</c>), whether or not they brought a camper into the park (<c>camper</c>), and the length of stay (<c>LOS</c>) were recorded for 250 camping parties. The data can be found in <c>fish2.csv</c>. Create and assess a model for the number of fish caught.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subexercises>
  </exercises>

</chapter>
